{{Use Canadian English|date=October 2018}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}} {{Infobox person | image = Jade Raymond Feb 2012-cropped.jpg | image_size = 250px | name = Jade Raymond | caption = Jade Raymond in 2012 | birth_name = Jade Raymond | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1975|8|28}} | birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada | employer = | occupation = | website = | alma_mater = [[McGill University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|B.S.]]) | title = }}
'''Jade Raymond''' (born 28 August 1975) is a Canadian [[video game producer]] and executive, and the founder of [[Ubisoft Toronto]] and [[Motive Studios]].
== Early life and career == Jade Raymond was born 28 August 1975 in [[Montreal]]<ref>{{cite news |last=Bjørn-Hansen |first=Søren |title=En kvinde blandt nørder |publisher=[[Metro International]] |date=6 November 2007 |language=Danish |url=http://metroxpress.dk/dk/article/2007/11/06/08/4143-66/index.xml |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080601011231/http://metroxpress.dk/dk/article/2007/11/06/08/4143-66/index.xml |archivedate=1 June 2008 |df=}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Bjørn-Hansen |first=Søren |title=En spelproducent som sticker ut från mängden |publisher=[[Metro International]] |date=8 November 2007 |language=Swedish |url=http://www.metro.se/se/article/2007/11/06/08/4736-48/index.xml}}</ref> She graduated from [[St. George's School of Montreal]] in 1992 and [[Marianopolis College]] in 1994. She received a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree from [[McGill University]] in 1998, where she majored in [[computer science]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alumnilive365.mcgill.ca/2009/10/27/jade-raymond-bsc98/ |title=JADE RAYMOND, BSc’98 |website=McGill Alumni Live 365 |date=27 October 2009 |accessdate=23 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722231223/http://www.alumnilive365.mcgill.ca/2009/10/27/jade-raymond-bsc98/ |archivedate=22 July 2015 |df=}}</ref> Her first post-university job was as a programmer for Sony, where she eventually helped in the creation of [[Sony Online]]'s first Research and Development group. This led to [[Electronic Arts]] where she worked as a producer on ''[[The Sims Online]]''. From 2003-2004, Raymond joined the [[G4 (U.S. TV channel)|G4]] program ''[[The Electric Playground]]'' as a part-time correspondent, working with [[Victor Lucas (television producer)|Victor Lucas]], [[Tommy Tallarico]] and [[Julie Stoffer]]. In 2004, she started working for [[Ubisoft Montreal]], where she led the creation of the first ''[[Assassin's Creed (video game)|Assassin's Creed]] game.'' Raymond went on to become executive producer on ''[[Assassin's Creed II]]'', and was executive producer of new IP at Ubisoft Montreal, which included ''[[Watch Dogs]]'' and ''[[The Mighty Quest for Epic Loot]]''.
In January 2010, Raymond moved to Toronto to build a new studio for Ubisoft in the role of managing director.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2013-09-06-how-to-build-a-aaa-studio |title=How to build a AAA studio |author=Brendan Sinclair |website=GameIndustry |date=6 September 2013 |accessdate=23 July 2015}}</ref> Raymond is also on the Board of Directors of [[WIFTI|WIFT]]-T, an organization dedicated the advancement of women across film, television and screen-based industries.
On 20 October 2014, Ubisoft and Raymond announced they were parting ways. Raymond did not announce at the time what she would be moving on to.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsledge.com/jade-raymond-ubisoft-split-alexandre-parizeau-tapped-replace-10429 |title=JADE RAYMOND AND UBISOFT SPLIT. ALEXANDRE PARIZEAU TAPPED TO REPLACE HER |publisher=Newsledge |date=20 October 2014 |first=Alex |last=Chavers |accessdate=23 November 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141021071720/http://www.newsledge.com/jade-raymond-ubisoft-split-alexandre-parizeau-tapped-replace-10429 |archivedate=21 October 2014 |df=}}</ref>
In July 2015, Raymond announced that she had joined [[Electronic Arts]] and formed [[Motive Studios]], based in Montreal. She was also to be in charge of [[Visceral Games]] studio, located in California, where she worked with games designer and writer [[Amy Hennig]] on [[Star Wars]] games<ref name="EA">{{cite web |url=http://www.ea.com/motivestudios/ |title=Motive Studios: Motive, Means And Opportunity |first=Jade |last=Raymond |publisher=[[Electronic Arts]] |accessdate=13 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://techraptor.net/content/jade-raymond-joins-electronic-arts-heads-new-studio |title=Jade Raymond Joins Electronic Arts; Heads New Studio |publisher=TechRaptor |last1=Grosso |first1=Robert |date=14 July 2015 |accessdate=31 July 2015}}</ref> and also develop new original IP, before the company was shut down by EA.<ref>https://kotaku.com/ea-shuts-down-visceral-games-1819623990</ref>
On 22 October 2018, it was confirmed that Jade Raymond left EA to pursue new opportunities.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/10/22/jade-raymond-leaves-ea-samantha-ryan-takes-over-montreal-studio/ |title=Jade Raymond leaves EA, Samantha Ryan takes over Montreal studio |publisher=Venturebeat |last=Takahashi |first=Dean |date=22 October 2018 |accessdate=22 October 2018}}</ref>
